{"title_page": "Electoral history of Pierre Trudeau", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About||the biography of Pierre Trudeau|Pierre Trudeau}}\n\n[[File:Pierre Trudeau (1975).jpg|thumb|right|Pierre Trudeau in 1975.]]\n\nThis article is the '''Electoral history of [[Pierre Trudeau]]''', the fifteenth [[Prime Minister of Canada]].\n\nA [[liberalism in Canada|Liberal]], he served two terms as Prime Minister (1968\u20131979;  1979-1984).  He led the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] in five general elections, winning four ([[1968 Canadian federal election|1968]], [[1972 Canadian federal election|1972]], [[1974 Canadian federal election|1974]] and [[1980 Canadian federal election|1980]]) and losing one ([[1979 Canadian federal election|1979]]).  He won majority governments in 1968, 1974 and 1980, and a minority government in the 1972 election.  With a total of fifteen years and 164 days in office, he is the third longest serving prime minister, after [[John A. Macdonald|Sir John A. Macdonald]].\n\nTrudeau succeeded [[Lester B. Pearson]] as prime minister in 1968.  After [[Joe Clark]] won the 1979 election, Trudeau resigned and became [[Leader of the Official Opposition (Canada)|Leader of the Opposition]].  The Clark government fell on a budget matter late in 1979 triggering the 1980 election, which returned Trudeau to office with a majority government.  He retired in 1984 and was succeeded as Liberal leader and prime minister by [[John Turner]].\n\nTrudeau stood for election to the [[House of Commons of Canada]] six times, all for the riding of [[Mount Royal (electoral district)|Mount Royal]] in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]].  He was elected with substantial majorities each time.\n\n== Summary ==\n\n[[File:Canada provinces 1949-1999.png|thumb|right|Canada had ten provinces and two territories throughout Trudeau's time as Prime Minister.]]\n\nTrudeau ranks third out of twenty-three prime ministers for [[List of Prime Ministers of Canada by time in office|time in office]], serving two terms totalling fifteen years and 164 days.<ref>[https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/People/primeMinisters PARLINFO:  Prime Ministers of Canada.]</ref>\n\nTrudeau was the fourth of four prime ministers to serve non-consecutive terms, the others being [[John A. Macdonald|Sir John A. Macdonald]], [[Arthur Meighen]] and [[William Lyon Mackenzie King]].\n\nTrudeau was the fourth of eight prime ministers from Quebec, the others being [[John Abbott|Sir John Abbott]], [[Wilfrid Laurier|Sir Wilfrid Laurier]], [[Louis St. Laurent]], [[Brian Mulroney]], [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], [[Paul Martin]] and [[Justin Trudeau]].  He was also the third of five francophone prime ministers, the others being Laurier, St. Laurent, Chr\u00e9tien, and Justin Trudeau.\n\nBefore entering politics, Trudeau was a federal public servant, an academic at the Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al and a social activist, particularly during the [[Asbestos Strike]] and as a founder and frequent contributor to the magazine ''[[Cit\u00e9 libre]]''.<ref name = DCB>[http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/trudeau_pierre_elliott_22E.html ''Dictionary of Canadian Biography'':  \"Trudeau, Pierre Elliot\".]</ref>  Along with two other colleagues from ''Cit\u00e9 libre'', [[Gerard Pelletier]] and [[Jean Marchand]], he was invited by Prime Minister [[Lester Pearson]] to join the Liberal government in Ottawa to combat the rising [[Quebec separatism]].  Trudeau stood for election in [[Mount Royal (electoral district)|Mount Royal]] in the [[1965 Canadian federal election|general election of 1965]], winning the seat.  Pearson appointed him as his [[parliamentary secretary]] and then [[Minister of Justice (Canada)|Minister of Justice]].  Following Pearson's announcement of his retirement in 1968, Trudeau ran for the leadership of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal party]] with Pearson's tacit support.<ref name = DCB-Pearson>[http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/pearson_lester_bowles_20E.html ''Dictionary of Canadian Biography'':  \"Pearson, Lester Bowles\".]</ref>   He won the leadership at the [[1968 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|Liberal leadership convention of 1968]] and became Prime Minister.<ref name = DCB/>\n\nTrudeau led the Liberals in five general elections. He was successful in the general elections of 1968, 1972 (albeit with a minority government), and 1974, but was defeated by [[Joe Clark]] in the 1979 election.  However, Clark's minority government was defeated late in 1979, triggering another election in early 1980, which Trudeau won.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/opinion/2009/12/11/behind_the_fall_of_joe_clark.html Allan McEachern, \"Behind the fall of Joe Clark\", ''Toronto Star'', December 11, 2009.]</ref>\n\nTrudeau stood for election to the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] six times (1965, 1968, 1972, 1974, 1979 and 1980), each time in the riding of [[Mount Royal (electoral district)|Mount Royal]] in Montreal, Quebec.  He was elected with substantial majorities each election.  His lowest vote count, in the 1965 election, was 55.6%, out of a field of four candidates.  In his next election, in 1968 at the height of [[Trudeaumania]], he received 90.8% of the votes in the riding.  In the next four elections, he received over 70% in one election (1974), and over 80% of the votes in three elections (1972, 1979 and 1980).  Trudeau served in the House of Commons for 18 years, 7 months and 22 days.<ref>[https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/People/Profile?personId=6230 PARLINFO:  The Right Hon. Pierre Elliott Trudeau, P.C., Q.C., C.C., F.R.S.C.]</ref>\n\nTrudeau won the Liberal leadership at the [[1968 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|1968 Liberal leadership convention]], from a field of nine candidates.  Trudeau won on the fourth ballot by the narrow margin of 51.1% over the runner-up, [[Robert Winters]], who had 40.6% of the votes.  Future prime minister [[John Turner]] came in third, with 8.3% of the votes.  As Liberal leader, Trudeau then became prime minister.\n\n== Federal general elections: 1968 to 1980 ==\n\n===Federal election, 1968 ===\n\n{{About||more detailed tables of election results|Canadian federal election, 1968}}\n{{About||information about the 28th Parliament, 1968 to 1972|28th Canadian Parliament}}\n{{About||information about Trudeau and political events during the 28th Parliament|Pierre Trudeau#Prime Minister, 1968-74}}\n\nTrudeau was elected leader of the Liberal Party on April 6, 1968.  He called the election shortly afterwards and won a majority, defeating the Progressive Conservatives led by [[Robert L. Stanfield]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ Canadian Federal Election, 1968 - Parties, Leaders, Seats Won and Popular Vote\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Leaders!!Seats Won!!Popular Vote\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}}\n|[[Pierre Trudeau]]<sup>1</sup>||align=center|154||align=center|45.4%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]]||[[Robert L. Stanfield]]<sup>2</sup>||align=center|72||align=center|31.4%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|NDP|row}}\n|[[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]]||[[Tommy Douglas]]||align=center|22||align=center|17.0%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Social Credit|row}}\n|[[Ralliement cr\u00e9ditiste]]||[[R\u00e9al Caouette]]||align=center|14||align=center|4.4%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent politician|Independent]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|0.5%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row}}\n| [[Liberal-Labour (Canada)|Liberal-Labour]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|0.1%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=left|Total\n! align=center|264\n! align=center|98.8%<sup>3</sup>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Sources:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/HFER.asp Library of Parliament \u2013 History of Federal Ridings since 1867]\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> Prime Minister when election was called;  Prime Minister after election.<br />\n<sup>2</sup>  Leader of the Opposition when election was called;  Leader of the Opposition after the election.<br />\n<sup>3</sup> Table does not include parties which received votes but did not elect any members.\n\n===Federal election, 1972 ===\n\n{{About||more detailed tables of election results|Canadian federal election, 1972}}\n{{About||information about the 29th Parliament, 1973 to 1974|29th Canadian Parliament}}\n{{About||information about Trudeau and political events during the 29rd Parliament|Pierre Trudeau#Prime Minister, 1968-74}}\n\nTrudeau led the Liberals in the 1972 election and was returned to office, but with a minority government.  Stanfield and the Progressive Conservatives won only two seats less than the Liberals.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ Canadian Federal Election, 1972 - Parties, Leaders, Seats Won and Popular Vote\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Leaders!!Seats Won!!Popular Vote\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}}\n|[[Pierre Trudeau]]<sup>1</sup>||align=center|109||align=center|38.4%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]]||[[Robert L. Stanfield]]<sup>2</sup>||align=center|107||align=center|35.0%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|NDP|row}}\n|[[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]]||[[David Lewis (politician)|David Lewis]]||align=center|31||align=center|17.8%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Social Credit|row-name}}\n|[[R\u00e9al Caouette]]||align=center|15||align=center|7.6%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent politician|Independent]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|0.6%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|No affiliation||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|0.3%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=left|Total\n! align=center|264