adian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent politician|Independent]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|0.4%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=left|Total\n! align=center|264\n! align=center|99.6%<sup>3</sup>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Sources:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/HFER.asp Library of Parliament \u2013 History of Federal Ridings since 1867]\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> Prime Minister when election was called;  Prime Minister after election.<br />\n<sup>2</sup>  Leader of the Opposition when election was called;  Leader of the Opposition after the election.<br />\n<sup>3</sup> Table does not include parties which received votes but did not elect any members.\n\n===Federal election, 1979 ===\n\n{{About||more detailed tables of election results|Canadian federal election, 1979}}\n{{About||information about the 31st Parliament, October to December, 1979|31st Canadian Parliament}}\n{{About||information about Trudeau and political events during the 31st Parliament|Pierre Trudeau#Defeat and Opposition}}\n\nTrudeau led the Liberals in the 1979 election and was defeated.  He resigned as Prime Minister.  [[Joe Clark]], the new leader of the Progressive Conservatives, formed a short-lived minority government.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ Canadian Federal Election, 1979 - Parties, Leaders, Seats Won and Popular Vote\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Leaders!!Seats Won!!Popular Vote\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]]||[[Joe Clark]]<sup>1</sup>||align=center|136||align=center|35.9%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}}\n|[[Pierre Trudeau]]<sup>2</sup>||align=center|114||align=center|40.1%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|NDP|row}}\n|[[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]]||[[Ed Broadbent]]||align=center|26||align=center|17.9%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Social Credit|row-name}}\n|[[Fabien Roy]]||align=center|6||align=center|4.6%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=left|Total\n! align=center|282\n! align=center|98.5%<sup>3</sup>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Sources:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/HFER.asp Library of Parliament \u2013 History of Federal Ridings since 1867]\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> Leader of the Opposition when election was called;  Prime Minister after election.<br />\n<sup>2</sup> Prime Minister when election was called;  Leader of the Opposition after the election.<br />\n<sup>3</sup> Table does not include parties which received votes but did not elect any members.\n\n===Federal election, 1980 ===\n\n{{About||more detailed tables of election results|Canadian federal election, 1980}}\n{{About||information about the 32nd Parliament, 1980 to 1984|32nd Canadian Parliament}}\n{{About||information about Trudeau and political events during the 32nd Parliament|Pierre Trudeau#Return to power, 1980\u201384}}\n\nAfter the 1979 election, Trudeau indicated he would resign as party leader, but would stay on as interim Leader of the Opposition.  However, before the Liberals could elect a new leader, the Clark government fell in December 1979 when the opposition parties defeated the budget in the Commons.  Trudeau led the Liberals in the resulting election and was returned to power with a majority. Clark became the Leader of the Opposition.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ Canadian Federal Election, 1980 - Parties, Leaders, Seats Won and Popular Vote\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Leaders!!Seats Won!!Popular Vote\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}}\n|[[Pierre Trudeau]]<sup>1</sup>||align=center|147||align=center|44.3%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]]||[[Joe Clark]]<sup>2</sup>||align=center|103||align=center|32.5%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|NDP|row}}\n|[[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]]||[[Ed Broadbent]]||align=center|32||align=center|19.8%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=left|Total\n! align=center|282\n! align=center|96.6%<sup>3</sup>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Sources:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/HFER.asp Library of Parliament \u2013 History of Federal Ridings since 1867]\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> Leader of the Opposition when election was called;  Prime Minister after election.<br />\n<sup>2</sup> Prime Minister when election was called;  Leader of the Opposition after the election.<br />\n<sup>3</sup> Table does not include parties which received votes but did not elect any members.\n\n== Federal constituency elections, 1965 to 1980 ==\n\nTrudeau stood for election to the House of Commons six times, starting with the general election of 1967. He was elected all six times, all from the riding of [[Mount Royal (electoral district)|Mount Royal]], in Montreal, Quebec.\n\n=== 1965 Federal Election: Mount Royal ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ [[1965 Canadian federal election|Federal Election, 1965]]: [[Mount Royal (electoral district)|Mount Royal]], Quebec\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Candidate!!Popular Vote!! % \n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}} \n||[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] [[Pierre Trudeau]]||align=center|28,064||align=center|55.6%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|NDP|row}}\n|[[New Democratic Party]]||[[Charles Taylor (philosopher)|Charles Taylor]]||align=center|14,929||align=center|29.6%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]]||Peter S. Wise||align=center|6,840||align=center|13.6%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Social Credit|row}}\n|[[Ralliement Cr\u00e9ditiste]]||Michel Smith||align=center|598||align=center|1.2%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=center|Total!! align=right|50,431!! align=right|100.0%\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Source:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/hfer.asp?Language=E&Search=Det&Include=Y&rid=454 Library of Parliament &ndash; His