/ |work=Buffalo Commercial |location=Buffalo, NY |url-access=subscription  |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Parker Men Here\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=August 3, 1911 |title=Death Notice, Edward Murphy, Jr. |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/313159604/ |work=The Central New Jersey Home News |location=New Brunswick, NJ |url-access=subscription  |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Death Notice, Edward Murphy, Jr.\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=August 6, 1911 |title=Edward Murphy, Jr. Buried |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/208656052/ |work=[[The Sun (New York City)|The Sun]] |location=New York, NY |url-access=subscription  |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Edward Murphy, Jr. Buried\"}}}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{CongBio|M001090|Edward Murphy}}\n*{{Findagrave|7254673}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef | before=William Kemp}}\n{{S-ttl | title=Mayor of [[Troy, New York]] | years=1875\u20131883}}\n{{S-aft | after=Edmund Fitzgerald}}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Charles C. B. Walker]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[New York State Democratic Committee]] Chairman|years=May 1888 \u2013 September 1894}}\n{{S-aft|after=James W. Hinckley}}\n{{S-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. Senator box| before=[[Frank Hiscock]]| class=1| state=New York| years=1893\u20131899| after=[[Chauncey Depew]]|alongside=[[David B. Hill]], [[Thomas C. Platt]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{USSenNY}}\n\n{{New York State Democratic Committee}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murphy, Edward}}\n[[Category:1836 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Fordham University alumni]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Troy, New York]]\n[[Category:United States senators from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Murphy_Jr."}
{"title_page": "La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta\n| type       = cover\n| artist     = [[Freddy Fender]]\n| cover      = Baldemar_Huerta.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 12, 2002\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]], [[Bolero]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Virgin Records|Back Porch]]\n| producer   = [[Michael Morales (musician)|Michael Morales]], Joe Reyes, Freddy Fender, Ron Morales\n| prev_title = Best of Freddy Fender Wasted Days and Wasted Nights\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = Secret Love: Live\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score ={{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Review\">{{Cite web |title=La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/la-musica-de-baldemar-huerta-mw0000217974 |work=Allmusic |publisher=Macrovision Corporation |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta''''' (\"The Music of Baldemar Huerta\") is the title of the [[Grammy Award|Grammy Award recipient]] [[cover album]] released by performer [[Freddy Fender]] on February 12, 2002.\n\n==Album history==\nOn this album, Freddy Fender pays homage to the music of his youth, songs he heard growing up in the [[R\u00edo Grande]] valley. About the recording sessions, the singer told ''Billboard'' magazine: \"Ten songs are what you call boleros, mainly from the '50s, and there are a couple from the '40s.\" ''La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta'' also features two songs in English language, \"Secret Love\" and \"Before the Next Teardrop Falls\", country music with [[mariachi]] guitars. \"It's really nice. The rest of them are love songs. I have maybe one that's a fast song, but it's still about love.\", the singer said.<ref name=\"Hot\">{{Cite web|title=Hot Product |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76836/hot-product |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=2009-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006072522/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76836/hot-product |archivedate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nFender connected with producers [[Michael Morales (musician)|Michael]] and Ron Morales because they had worked with the [[Texas Tornados]], as well as Tornado member [[Flaco Jim\u00e9nez]]. \"I did the vocals with just the guitar,\" Fender told about the recording in his hometown of [[Corpus Christi, Texas]]. \"Then in San Antonio they put harmonies on it, and both Ron and Michael put some more instruments on it. They even put strings and horns, and then the mariachi background. They did one hell of a job.\"<ref name=\"Hot\"/>\n\n''La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta'' was issued in limited release via Studio M Recordings before being picked up by [[Virgin Records|Back Porch/Virgin]]. The regional release made it eligible to achieve the Grammy nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|in the best Latin pop album category]] which it won.<ref name=\"Review\"/><ref name=\"Hot\"/> By the time of the [[Grammy Awards of 2001]] ceremony, Fender was still recovering from a [[kidney transplant]] surgery.<ref name=\"Hot\"/> This trophy was the first Grammy Award that Fender won as a solo artist; previous to this the artist won two [[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Best Mexican-American performance awards]] for group efforts with [[Texas Tornados]] and [[Los Super Seven]].<ref name=\"Celebrate\">{{Cite web|title=Fender Recovering, Celebrating First Solo Grammy |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76634/fender-recovering-celebrating-first-solo-grammy |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |last=Jeckell |first=Barry A. |date=2002-02-28 |accessdate=2009-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141005171306/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76634/fender-recovering-celebrating-first-solo-grammy |archivedate=October 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nFor the artist, the Grammy was a long time coming. \"I really feel great. I've been going to the Grammys off and on since the '70s and been wanting to win one since then,\" Fender told Billboard.com. \"I was nominated in '75, but [[Captain & Tennille]] won [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|record of the year]] for \"[[Love Will Keep Us Together]]\". And in '76, I was up again, but [[Stevie Wonder]] took it. I won the awards with the Tornados and Super Seven, but this is my first individual win, and that really makes me feel real nice and warm.\"<ref name=\"Celebrate\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| title1          = Rayito de Luna\n| writer1         = J.J. \"Cucho\" Navarro\n| length1         = 3:11\n| title2          = [[Perfidia]]\n| writer2         = Alberto Dom\u00ednguez\n| length2         = 3:19\n| title3          = Cien A\u00f1os\n| writer3         = Alberto Cervantes, [[Rub\u00e9n Fuentes]]\n| length3         = 3:02\n| title4          = Recuerdos de Ipacairi\n| writer4         = Zulema de Mirkin, Demetrio Ort\u00edz\n| length4         = 3:30\n| title5          = Cien Mujeres\n| writer5         = [[Alfredo Gil]]\n| length5         = 3:13\n| title6          = Amor P\u00e9rdido\n| writer6         = [[Pedro Flores (composer)|Pedro Flores]]\n| length6         = 3:33\n| title7          = Noche de Ronda\n| writer7         = [[Agust\u00edn Lara]]\n| length7         = 2:57\n| title8          = Siete Notas de Amor\n| writer8         = Santiago Alvarado\n| length8         = 3:18\n| title9          = Despedida\n| writer9         = Flores\n| length9         = 3:33\n| title10         = Adi\u00f3s Muchachos\n| writer10        = Cesar Sanders, Caesar Vedani\n| length10        = 3:09\n| title11         = [[Before the Next Teardrop Falls (song)|Before the Next Teardrop Falls]]\n| writer11        = Vivian Keith, Ben Peters\n| length11        = 2:35\n| title12         = [[Secret Love (1953 song)|Secret Love]]\n| writer12        = [[Sammy Fain]], [[Paul Francis Webster]]\n| length12        = 3:34\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nThe following people contributed to ''La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta'':<ref name=\"Review\"/>\n*Michael Morales \u2013 [[percussion]], [[vocals]], [[Record producer|producer]], [[engineer]], [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n*Ron Morales \u2013 vocals, producer, engineer, mixing  \n*Joe Reyes \u2013 guitar, vocals, producer, engineer  \n*Jerre Hall \u2013 [[creative consultant]]\n*Bill Hoover \u2013 [[executive producer]]\n*Clayton Hoover \u2013 executive producer  \n*CJ \u2013 [[digital editing]]\n*Mark Sadler \u2013 studio project manager\n*Juan A. Aguilar \u2013 [[guitar]]\n*Freddy Fender \u2013 [[vocals]]\n*Bobby Flores \u2013 [[violin]], orchestral arrangements\n*Al Gomez \u2013 [[trumpet]]\n*Francisco \"Pancho\" Perez \u2013 [[guitarr\u00f3n]]\n*John Schattenberg \u2013 violin\n*Chepe Solis & San Antonio \u2013 guitar, [[requinto]]\n*Gabriel Zavala \u2013 percussion, [[accordion]]\n*Kurt Pfeifer \u2013 [[art direction]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Freddy Fender}} \n{{DEFAULTSORT:Musica De Baldemar Huerta}}\n[[Category:2002 albums]]\n[[Category:Freddy Fender albums]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language albums]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album]]\n[[Category:Covers albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta\n| type       = cover\n| artist     = [[Freddy Fender]]\n| cover      = Baldemar_Huerta.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 12, 2002\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]], [[Bolero]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Virgin Records|Back Porch]]\n| producer   = [[Michael Morales (musician)|Michael Morales]], Joe Reyes, Freddy Fender, Ron Morales\n| prev_title = Best of Freddy Fender Wasted Days and Wasted Nights\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = Secret Love: Live\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score ={{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Review\">{{Cite web |title=La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r570111|pure_url=yes}} |work=Allmusic |publisher=Macrovision Corporation |accessdate=2009-01-22}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta''''' (\"The Music of Baldemar Huerta\") is the title of the [[Grammy Award|Grammy Award recipient]] [[cover album]] released by performer [[Freddy Fender]] on February 12, 2002.\n\n==Album history==\nOn this album, Freddy Fender pays homage to the music of his youth, songs he heard growing up in the [[R\u00edo Grande]] valley. About the recording sessions, the singer told ''Billboard'' magazine: \"Ten songs are what you call boleros, mainly from the '50s, and there are a couple from the '40s.\" ''La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta'' also features two songs in English language, \"Secret Love\" and \"Before the Next Teardrop Falls\", country music with [[mariachi]] guitars. \"It's really nice. The rest of them are love songs. I have maybe one that's a fast song, but it's still about love.\", the singer said.<ref name=\"Hot\">{{Cite web|title=Hot Product |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76836/hot-product |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=2009-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006072522/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76836/hot-product |archivedate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nFender connected with producers [[Michael Morales (musician)|Michael]] and Ron Morales because they had worked with the [[Texas Tornados]], as well as Tornado member [[Flaco Jim\u00e9nez]]. \"I did the vocals with just the guitar,\" Fender told about the recording in his hometown of [[Corpus Christi, Texas]]. \"Then in San Antonio they put harmonies on it, and both Ron and Michael put some more instruments on it. They even put strings and horns, and then the mariachi background. They did one hell of a job.\"<ref name=\"Hot\"/>\n\n''La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta'' was issued in limited release via Studio M Recordings before being picked up by [[Virgin Records|Back Porch/Virgin]]. The regional release made it eligible to achieve the Grammy nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|in the best Latin pop album category]] which it won.<ref name=\"Review\"/><ref name=\"Hot\"/> By the time of the [[Grammy Awards of 2001]] ceremony, Fender was still recovering from a [[kidney transplant]] surgery.<ref name=\"Hot\"/> This trophy was the first Grammy Award that Fender won as a solo artist; previous to this the artist won two [[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Best Mexican-American performance awards]] for group efforts with [[Texas Tornados]] and [[Los Super Seven]].<ref name=\"Celebrate\">{{Cite web|title=Fender Recovering, Celebrating First Solo Grammy |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76634/fender-recovering-celebrating-first-solo-grammy |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |last=Jeckell |first=Barry A. |date=2002-02-28 |accessdate=2009-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141005171306/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/76634/fender-recovering-celebrating-first-solo-grammy |archivedate=October 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nFor the artist, the Grammy was a long time coming. \"I really feel great. I've been going to the Grammys off and on since the '70s and been wanting to win one since then,\" Fender told Billboard.com. \"I was nominated in '75, but [[Captain & Tennille]] won [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|record of the year]] for \"[[Love Will Keep Us Together]]\". And in '76, I was up again, but [[Stevie Wonder]] took it. I won the awards with the Tornados and Super Seven, but this is my first individual win, and that really makes me feel real nice and warm.\"<ref name=\"Celebrate\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| title1          = Rayito de Luna\n| writer1         = J.J. \"Cucho\" Navarro\n| length1         = 3:11\n| title2          = [[Perfidia]]\n| writer2         = Alberto Dom\u00ednguez\n| length2         = 3:19\n| title3          = Cien A\u00f1os\n| writer3         = Alberto Cervantes, [[Rub\u00e9n Fuentes]]\n| length3         = 3:02\n| title4          = Recuerdos de Ipacairi\n| writer4         = Zulema de Mirkin, Demetrio Ort\u00edz\n| length4         = 3:30\n| title5          = Cien Mujeres\n| writer5         = [[Alfredo Gil]]\n| length5         = 3:13\n| title6          = Amor P\u00e9rdido\n| writer6         = [[Pedro Flores (composer)|Pedro Flores]]\n| length6         = 3:33\n| title7          = Noche de Ronda\n| writer7         = [[Agust\u00edn Lara]]\n| length7         = 2:57\n| title8          = Siete Notas de Amor\n| writer8         = Santiago Alvarado\n| length8         = 3:18\n| title9          = Despedida\n| writer9         = Flores\n| length9         = 3:33\n| title10         = Adi\u00f3s Muchachos\n| writer10        = Cesar Sanders, Caesar Vedani\n| length10        = 3:09\n| title11         = [[Before the Next Teardrop Falls (song)|Before the Next Teardrop Falls]]\n| writer11        = Vivian Keith, Ben Peters\n| length11        = 2:35\n| title12         = [[Secret Love (1953 song)|Secret Love]]\n| writer12        = [[Sammy Fain]], [[Paul Francis Webster]]\n| length12        = 3:34\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nThe following people contributed to ''La M\u00fasica de Baldemar Huerta'':<ref name=\"Review\"/>\n*Michael Morales \u2013 [[percussion]], [[vocals]], [[Record producer|producer]], [[engineer]], [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n*Ron Morales \u2013 vocals, producer, engineer, mixing  \n*Joe Reyes \u2013 guitar, vocals, producer, engineer  \n*Jerre Hall \u2013 [[creative consultant]]\n*Bill Hoover \u2013 [[executive producer]]\n*Clayton Hoover \u2013 executive producer  \n*CJ \u2013 [[digital editing]]\n*Mark Sadler \u2013 studio project manager\n*Juan A. Aguilar \u2013 [[guitar]]\n*Freddy Fender \u2013 [[vocals]]\n*Bobby Flores \u2013 [[